-- в”Ђв”Ђ Eleventy в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Eleventy (11ty) is a free, open-source JavaScript static site generator designed to be simpler and more flexible than alternatives like Jekyll, supporting many template languages out of the box.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Eleventy (11ty) Review 2026: Features & Setup Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Eleventy (11ty) explained: the free, open-source JavaScript static site generator that supports 10+ template languages and zero-config builds.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Eleventy, commonly abbreviated 11ty, is a free and open-source static site generator built in JavaScript. It was created in 2017 by developer Zach Leatherman, who was inspired by Ruby-based Jekyll and wanted an equally simple but more flexible tool built natively for the JavaScript ecosystem. The name is a personal touch: Leatherman has explained that 'Eleventy' comes from a childhood mispronunciation of the number eleven that his grandmother liked to retell as a story, giving the otherwise technical project a distinctly playful identity. Unlike many modern JavaScript frameworks, Eleventy was deliberately designed around minimal configuration, fast build times, and zero required client-side JavaScript, which made it a favorite among developers who wanted fast, simple, content-focused websites without adopting a full framework like Next.js or Gatsby.

Technically, Eleventy works by reading a directory of source files, most commonly written in Markdown, Nunjucks, Liquid, Handlebars, Pug, EJS, HAML, or plain HTML, and compiling them into static HTML files that can be hosted anywhere, including free static hosts, CDNs, or traditional web servers. A defining feature is that it supports more than ten templating languages simultaneously in the same project, and, critically, it does not force any particular front-end framework or build tooling on the developer. Data can be layered in through JSON, JavaScript, or front-matter files, and Eleventy's data cascade system lets developers compose global, directory-level, and per-page data cleanly. Because Eleventy ships no client-side JavaScript by default, sites built with it tend to score very well on page-speed and Core Web Vitals metrics, which has made it a popular choice for content sites, documentation, blogs, and marketing pages where SEO performance matters.

Eleventy is entirely free and open source, distributed under the MIT license, with its source code hosted on GitHub. There is no paid tier, subscription, or commercial edition of the core tool; anyone can install it via npm and use it for personal or commercial projects at no cost. In September 2024, the project entered a new chapter of its history when Font Awesome, the icon and web-tooling company, acquired the project's stewardship, and Zach Leatherman joined the Font Awesome team to continue leading its development while keeping the tool open source. In October 2024, Eleventy released version 3.0, its first major version to natively support ECMAScript modules, followed by continued performance-focused releases such as version 3.1, described by the maintainers as measurably faster and smaller than prior releases.

In March 2026, Font Awesome introduced a rebrand of the project under the name 'Build Awesome,' positioning it as an all-in-one site-building companion to Font Awesome and Web Awesome products. The rebrand proved controversial within the developer community, and shortly afterward Font Awesome paused both an associated crowdfunding campaign and the renaming plans following concerns that promotional emails to the community had not reached their intended recipients as expected. As of mid-2026, the project continues to be actively maintained, with the 11ty name still very much in active use across its documentation, plugin ecosystem, and community resources, even as its long-term branding direction remains an open conversation.

Eleventy's primary users are web developers, technical writers, and small teams building blogs, documentation sites, marketing pages, and portfolios who want full control over their HTML output without the overhead of a JavaScript framework. It is frequently used in the Jamstack ecosystem alongside static hosts like Netlify and Vercel. Its closest competitors include Jekyll (Ruby-based, one of the original static site generators), Hugo (Go-based, known for extremely fast builds), Astro and Next.js (which output static or hybrid sites but center around component-based frameworks), and Gatsby. Eleventy differentiates itself through its unopinionated, framework-agnostic approach, its support for many templating languages in a single project, and its historically minimal learning curve compared to component-framework-based generators. Because it produces plain HTML with no required JavaScript runtime, it remains one of the most SEO- and performance-friendly static site generators available, and it continues to be maintained as a genuinely free, community- and Font Awesome-backed open-source project rather than a venture-funded commercial product.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'd95e837c-ef43-455b-89b5-3d198bab18ed';

