-- в”Ђв”Ђ Ellie Planner в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Ellie is a daily planner app that combines a brain-dump task list with a drag-and-drop Kanban-style day timeline, built by solo developer Chris Raroque for iOS, macOS, Windows, and the web.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Pro from $9.99/month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1 (solo founder)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Dallas, Texas, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Ellie Planner Review 2026: Features & Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Ellie Planner reviewed: the brain-dump and drag-and-drop daily planner app for iOS, macOS, Windows and web, with pricing and feature breakdown for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Ellie Planner, usually referred to simply as Ellie, is a personal daily-planning application built around two core ideas: a free-form 'brain dump' area for capturing every task and thought without friction, and a visual, drag-and-drop day timeline for turning that unstructured list into a realistic schedule. The app was built by Chris Raroque, a Dallas, Texas-based solo indie developer who has also worked on other software projects, including an earlier app called Mogul and a venture-focused startup called Aloa. Ellie began as a personal side project to solve Raroque's own struggle with traditional to-do list apps, which tend to let unfinished tasks pile up indefinitely without ever forcing a realistic look at how much time is actually available in a day. According to Raroque's own account of building the product, Ellie grew organically to several hundred daily active users while being run and supported largely by a single developer, a detail that has made it a frequently cited example in indie-maker and solo-SaaS-builder communities.

Functionally, Ellie works around a simple daily loop. Users start by dumping every task, idea, or to-do into an unstructured 'braindump' list, without needing to assign times or priorities upfront. From there, tasks are dragged onto a visual timeline or Kanban-style day board, effectively timeboxing each item into a specific block of the day. This design is meant to combat the common failure mode of long, static to-do lists, where tasks accumulate without ever being scheduled into real time. Ellie also supports recurring tasks, subtasks, due dates, unlimited labels for organizing tasks by project or context, and basic time tracking with lightweight analytics on how time is actually spent across a day or week. To fit into an existing digital calendar workflow, Ellie integrates with Google Calendar and Apple Calendar, and it supports Siri Shortcuts for quick task capture on Apple devices.

Ellie is available as a native iOS app for iPhone and iPad, a native macOS app, a Windows application, and a web app, giving it broader desktop coverage than many competing planner apps; notably, there is no native Android app, so Android users are limited to the web version. This platform spread, particularly the inclusion of dedicated macOS and Windows apps alongside iOS, differentiates Ellie from many mobile-first productivity apps that treat desktop as an afterthought.

On pricing, Ellie follows a freemium model. The Free plan allows unlimited task creation and access to the core braindump workflow across the iOS and web apps at no cost and without requiring a credit card. The paid tier, Ellie Pro, unlocks the full timeboxing/timebox mode, both calendar integrations, unlimited labels and subtasks, recurring tasks, and due dates. Ellie Pro is offered as a $9.99 per month subscription, or as a one-time lifetime purchase for a higher upfront price rather than a recurring monthly fee, giving users who dislike subscriptions a way to pay once. The company also offers a 50% discount off the yearly price for students who verify their status by contacting support directly.

Ellie's target users are individuals who have struggled with conventional to-do list apps and want a lighter-weight, more visual way to plan a single day at a time, rather than a heavyweight project-management tool built for teams. It appeals particularly to knowledge workers, freelancers, students, and anyone practicing timeboxing or time-blocking as a personal productivity method. Its closest competitors include Todoist and TickTick for general task management, Sunsama and Motion for calendar-integrated daily planning, and Structured for its similarly visual timeline-based approach to daily scheduling. Ellie differentiates itself with its explicit two-step brain-dump-then-schedule workflow, its native multi-platform desktop support beyond just mobile, and its origin and continued operation as a lean, largely solo-built product rather than a venture-backed team, which has kept its feature set focused and its pricing comparatively simple.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cdc946d2-b06d-4438-be5e-2091531fcf59';

