-- в”Ђв”Ђ EmailRelay в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$E-MailRelay is a free, open-source, lightweight SMTP proxy and store-and-forward mail transfer agent written in C++ for Linux and Windows, often used as a local spam-filtering relay.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$EmailRelay Review 2026: Open-Source SMTP Relay$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$E-MailRelay explained: the free, open-source C++ SMTP proxy and store-and-forward mail server for Linux and Windows, with features and setup guidance.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$E-MailRelay, referred to on gappsy as EmailRelay, is a free and open-source SMTP proxy and store-and-forward mail transfer agent (MTA) written in C++. It is distributed and versioned through SourceForge, where its releases for both Linux and Windows are hosted, including a graphical installation wizard for Windows users who prefer not to configure the software from the command line. Unlike large, general-purpose mail servers such as Postfix or Exim, E-MailRelay is intentionally narrow in scope: it is built to sit between a mail source and a destination mail server, receiving, storing, and forwarding email messages, rather than trying to be a full-featured mailbox or webmail platform.

Architecturally, E-MailRelay runs as a single, lightweight process using the same non-blocking input/output model employed by high-performance software like Squid and nginx, which gives it strong scalability and a small resource footprint even on modest hardware. It performs three related jobs: acting as an SMTP storage daemon that accepts and stores incoming email, acting as an SMTP forwarding agent that relays stored messages onward to another server, and acting as a POP3 server that lets local email client software retrieve the stored messages. Forwarding is typically configured to a fixed 'smarthost,' a designated upstream mail server responsible for final delivery, though E-MailRelay can also be configured to perform its own routing logic when needed. A notable capability is its support for passing every message through a user-defined external program before it is forwarded; this hook lets administrators plug in spam filters such as SpamAssassin, or write custom scripts that can drop, re-address, or otherwise edit messages as they pass through the relay. It also supports DNSBL-based connection blocking to reject connections from known spam sources at the network level.

Because of this design, E-MailRelay is most commonly deployed in a handful of specific scenarios: as a personal or small-office internet mail server that filters spam before final delivery, as a local development or testing SMTP server that captures outbound mail from applications without actually delivering it externally, and as a lightweight relay/proxy sitting in front of a heavier production mail server to add filtering or store-and-forward resilience. Its C++ codebase and minimal dependencies make it straightforward to compile and run on constrained systems, including older hardware or embedded Linux environments, where a full mail server stack like Postfix would be comparatively heavyweight.

E-MailRelay is entirely free and open source, and there is no commercial edition, paid tier, or licensing fee associated with the software; users download source or pre-built binaries directly from its SourceForge project page at no cost. As is common for smaller, long-running open-source infrastructure projects, there is no dedicated company behind it, no disclosed founding date beyond its long-standing presence on SourceForge, and no formal support contracts вЂ” support comes from project documentation and community channels rather than a commercial vendor.

E-MailRelay's target users are systems administrators, developers, and hobbyists who need a small, dependency-light SMTP relay or proxy rather than a full-featured mail server platform. It is frequently compared with Postfix, Exim, and sendmail, all of which are far more feature-complete general-purpose MTAs capable of running full production mail infrastructure, and with lighter developer-focused tools like MailHog or smtp4dev, which are built specifically for capturing outbound test email during software development. E-MailRelay's differentiation is its narrow, single-purpose design: it does one job вЂ” storing, filtering, and forwarding SMTP mail вЂ” extremely efficiently, with a small codebase, low resource usage, and straightforward configuration, rather than trying to compete with full mail server suites on breadth of features. This makes it a durable, low-maintenance choice for administrators who specifically need a relay or proxy layer rather than a complete mailbox and delivery system.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '48dce657-93e5-4f57-b7c7-2ec20c859674';

